---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "We have a batch of oil with diesel dissolved in it. Can your centrifuge separate the diesel from the oil?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Industrial Centrifuges work on the principle of different specific gravity separating into different phases under extremely high g-force. If you have dissolved liquids there is effectively no difference in specific gravity for the centrifuge to separate. Therefore centrifuges of any type cannot separate dissolved liquids or solids dissolved in liquids (i.e. Salt / Water)."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "We have oil with 25% or more sludge – can your self-cleaning centrifuge separate the oil from the sludge?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Self-Cleaning centrifuges are capable of separating up to 5% sludge (by volume) due to the inherent design of these types of centrifuges. For high sludge applications we recommend horizontal decanter type centrifuges which are capable of separating high sludge content fluids up to 30% or more in some cases."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the typical applications of a Manual Clean centrifuge?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "As the name implies, Manual Clean centrifuges are designed for liquid/liquid separation of 2 immiscible liquids with no solids or very low solids contamination (< 0.5% by volume). Typical applications include separation of water from diesel fuel; separation of water from turbine lube oil; biodiesel separation from glycerin etc."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the typical applications of a Self Cleaning centrifuge?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Self Cleaning Centrifuges have more extensive uses. They are designed for liquid/liquid/solid separation. Though these are self cleaning centrifuges, they can separate fluids with up to 5% (by volume) solids. Any ratio of the 2 immiscible liquids can typically be handled by these types of centrifuges. Typical applications include separation of crude-oil from salt-water and sediment; fuel oil separation from water and sediment; WVO separation from water and sediment; used motor oil separation from water and fine metal particles etc."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the typical applications of a Decanter centrifuge?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Decanter centrifuges are widely used for applications with more than 5% solids (up to 50%) by volume. They are designed for 2 phase and 3 phase separation. Typical applications include crude oil tank bottom sludge; industrial and municipal wastewater; hemp biomass separation; chemical sludge thickening; oilfield drilling mud separation etc."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the utilities required for operation of industrial centrifuges? Do they consume a lot of power?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most industrial centrifuges operate on 460 Volts AC power. The small centrifuges (1-2 GPM) use 1 HP motor and the largest (100+ GPM) can have 50 HP or larger motors on them. Self-cleaning centrifuges need a clean, potable water supply for the sludge ejection mechanism. City water supply @ 50 psig is sufficient. Some systems with integral sludge tanks and sludge pumps require compressed air typically at 100 psig."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "We need to get a centrifuge for biodiesel separation – does the centrifuge need to be Explosion Proof?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Requirement of explosion proof components / systems are entirely defined by your local codes (or rules). Dolphin Centrifuge is unable to verify applicability of your local codes. The customer needs to contact the appropriate authorities to ascertain the requirement of such codes. Dolphin Centrifuge has in-house capability to design and manufacture explosion proof centrifuge systems."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who is Dolphin Centrifuge? How is Dolphin different from other centrifuge suppliers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dolphin Centrifuge is a Michigan incorporated company specializing in industrial centrifuges for over 35 years. Industrial Centrifuges is ALL WE DO. The main difference between Dolphin and other centrifuge suppliers is that Dolphin is essentially an engineering company specializing in industrial centrifuges. Dolphin has an inventory of over 300 good new, re-manufactured and used centrifuges of all sizes and types at our Warren, MI factory. Dolphin does not list equipment that it does not own."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can we see the centrifuge before we buy it?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Absolutely! All prospective customers are welcome to our Warren, MI factory to inspect our centrifuges. Customers are also invited to witness the testing of their centrifuge system at our facility prior to shipment."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can we see the centrifuge in operation, before we take delivery?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. In fact, we recommend our customers to visit our Warren, MI factory to see their centrifuges being tested. We also offer hands-on operational training at our factory at no charge to our customers."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Where is the Reconditioning, Fabrication and Manufacturing work done?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "All Re-manufacturing, Fabrication, Assembly, Control System Assembly, Wiring and Testing are done at our Warren, MI factory."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you provide on-site start-up and training? Is it included in the cost of the centrifuge?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In addition to the no-charge training available at the Dolphin Centrifuge factory in Warren, MI, we provide on-site start-up and training at your facility. These services are typically not included in the cost of the base centrifuge system, however we can provide a comprehensive proposal to include start-up and training, on customer request."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What about after-sales support? How long can we expect after-sales support and is there a charge?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dolphin Centrifuge is known for its free Life-time after-sales technical support which is included with all centrifuges supplied by us. We routinely get calls from customers who have been operating our centrifuge over many years."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do we know an industrial centrifuge will work for our process? Does Dolphin provide testing services?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "We have supplied centrifuges for over 35 years, for practically all centrifuge applications. We can often tell you if a centrifuge will work for your application based on our experience and the hundreds of sample tests we have performed over the years. Dolphin Centrifuge offers a sample testing service. As part of this service, we process a small sample (1 gal) of your product through our pilot scale disc stack centrifuge."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What kind of lead-times are expected from order to shipping for reconditioned centrifuge skids?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Typical lead-times for small centrifuges are in the 4-8 week range whereas larger centrifuges can be anywhere from 12-20 weeks depending on the scope of supply and options selected by the customer."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does pricing on your reconditioned centrifuges compare with new centrifuges from the OEM?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Generally you can expect our pricing for a reconditioned centrifuge system (with new skid, new pump, new controls and all new accessories) to be about 50% of similar capacity new centrifuge systems."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does Dolphin Centrifuge provide any kind of warranty with its reconditioned centrifuges?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, all our reconditioned centrifuges come with a 6-month mechanical warranty with a written warranty statement provided with the formal proposal."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do we know Dolphin Centrifuge won't disappear after they get our money? Can you provide references?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dolphin Centrifuge has been in the centrifuge business for over 35 years during which we have delivered hundreds of centrifuges throughout the world. Yes, we can provide references of customers who have been with Dolphin Centrifuge for years. You are also welcome to visit our facility before you make your final purchase decision. We highly recommend it."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Industrial Centrifuge FAQ | Dolphin Centrifuge"
  description="Answers to the most common questions about industrial centrifuges — types, applications, utilities, pricing, warranties, testing, and Dolphin Centrifuge's services."
  canonicalUrl="https://dolphincentrifuge.com/industrial-centrifuges-faq/"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'Knowledge Center', href: '/disc-stack-centrifuge-faq/' },
    { label: 'Industrial Centrifuge FAQ' }
  ]}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-[#1B3A5C] text-white py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container-dolphin max-w-4xl px-4 md:px-6">
      <nav class="text-sm text-blue-200 mb-4" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="flex flex-wrap gap-1 items-center list-none p-0 m-0">
          <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-white transition-colors">Home</a></li>
          <li class="text-blue-400">/</li>
          <li><a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-faq/" class="hover:text-white transition-colors">Knowledge Center</a></li>
          <li class="text-blue-400">/</li>
          <li class="text-white font-medium">Industrial Centrifuge FAQ</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold leading-tight mb-4">Industrial Centrifuge FAQ</h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-blue-100 max-w-2xl">
        Answers to the most common questions about industrial centrifuge types, applications, utilities,
        pricing, warranties, testing services, and how Dolphin Centrifuge differs from other suppliers.
      </p>
      <!-- TOC quick-jump -->
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href="#about-centrifuges" class="bg-white/10 hover:bg-white/20 transition-colors text-white text-sm font-medium px-4 py-2 rounded-lg border border-white/20">About Centrifuges</a>
        <a href="#about-dolphin" class="bg-white/10 hover:bg-white/20 transition-colors text-white text-sm font-medium px-4 py-2 rounded-lg border border-white/20">About Dolphin</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content -->
  <section class="bg-[#F5F5F0] py-12 md:py-16">
    <div class="container-dolphin max-w-4xl px-4 md:px-6">

      <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge answers frequently asked questions about industrial centrifuge selection, capacity sizing, G-force ratings, self-cleaning vs. manual-clean bowls, two-phase vs. three-phase separation, decanter vs. disc stack centrifuges, ROI, maintenance, and supplier evaluation. Based in Warren, Michigan, Dolphin Centrifuge has over 40 years of application engineering experience across fuel, coolant, lube oil, wastewater, and food processing industries.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Intro callout -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-10">
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Whether you're evaluating your first industrial centrifuge purchase or comparing Dolphin Centrifuge
          to other suppliers, this FAQ covers the questions our engineers hear most often. Browse by topic
          below or use the jump links to go straight to a section.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3 text-sm">
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C]">Sections:</span>
            <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-[#2D2D2D]">
              <li><a href="#about-centrifuges" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">FAQ About Industrial Centrifuges</a></li>
              <li><a href="#about-dolphin" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">FAQ About Dolphin Centrifuge</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C]">Related pages:</span>
            <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1">
              <li><a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-faq/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">Disc Stack Centrifuge FAQ</a></li>
              <li><a href="/industrial-centrifuge-sample-testing/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">Sample Testing Service</a></li>
              <li><a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-applications/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">Centrifuge Applications</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== SECTION 1: FAQ ABOUT INDUSTRIAL CENTRIFUGES ===== -->
      <div id="about-centrifuges" class="scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6 pb-3 border-b-2 border-[#E8A317]">FAQ About Industrial Centrifuges</h2>

        <!-- Q1 -->
        <div id="q-dissolved-diesel" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">
            We have a batch of oil with diesel dissolved in it. Can your centrifuge separate the diesel from the oil?
          </h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            Industrial Centrifuges work on the principle of different specific gravity separating into different
            phases under extremely high "g" force. If you have dissolved liquids there is effectively no
            difference in specific gravity for the centrifuge to separate. Therefore centrifuges of any type
            <strong>cannot separate dissolved liquids or solids dissolved in liquids</strong> (i.e. Salt / Water).
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            Visit our <a href="/diesel-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">diesel centrifuge</a> page
            to see examples of what diesel separation centrifuges <em>can</em> accomplish — removing free water
            and sediment from diesel fuel rather than separating dissolved components.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-4 bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm text-[#2D2D2D]">
            <strong class="text-[#E8A317]">Key principle:</strong> Centrifugal separation requires a density difference between phases. Dissolved substances share the same density as their solvent and cannot be separated by centrifugal force alone.
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Q2 -->
        <div id="q-high-sludge" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">
            We have oil with 25% or more sludge – can your "self-cleaning" centrifuge separate the oil from the sludge?
          </h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            "Self-Cleaning" centrifuges are capable of separating <strong>up to 5% sludge (by volume)</strong> due
            to the inherent design of these types of centrifuges. The sludge ejection ports and bowl geometry are
            optimized for low-to-moderate solids loading.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            For high sludge applications we recommend horizontal
            <a href="/alfa-laval-decanter-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">decanter type centrifuges</a>
            which are capable of separating high sludge content fluids <strong>up to 30% or more</strong> in some cases.
            Decanters use a continuous scroll conveyor to discharge solids, making them ideal for high-solids streams.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
              <thead>
                <tr class="bg-[#1B3A5C] text-white">
                  <th class="text-left px-4 py-2 rounded-tl-lg">Centrifuge Type</th>
                  <th class="text-left px-4 py-2">Max Solids (vol %)</th>
                  <th class="text-left px-4 py-2 rounded-tr-lg">Best For</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-100">
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Manual Clean (Clarifier)</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3">&lt; 0.5%</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3">Liquid/liquid, trace solids</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 bg-gray-50">
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Self-Cleaning (Purifier)</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3">Up to 5%</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3">Liquid/liquid/solid, moderate solids</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Decanter</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3">Up to 50%+</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3">High-solids slurries, sludge dewatering</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Q3 -->
        <div id="q-manual-clean" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">
            What are the typical applications of a "Manual Clean" centrifuge?
          </h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            As the name implies, "Manual Clean" centrifuges are designed for
            <strong>liquid/liquid separation of 2 immiscible liquids</strong> with no solids or very low solids
            contamination (&lt; 0.5% by volume). The bowl must be opened and cleaned manually when solids
            accumulate, so they are best suited to clean or nearly-clean feeds.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">Typical applications include:</p>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Separation of water from diesel fuel — see our <a href="/diesel-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">diesel centrifuge page</a></span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Separation of water from <a href="/lube-oil-purifier/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">turbine lube oil</a></span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span><a href="/biodiesel-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">Biodiesel separation</a> from glycerin</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Any clean liquid/liquid application where the feed contains minimal suspended solids</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Q4 -->
        <div id="q-self-cleaning" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">
            What are the typical applications of a "Self Cleaning" centrifuge?
          </h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            "Self Cleaning" Centrifuges have more extensive uses. They are designed for
            <strong>liquid/liquid/solid separation</strong>. Though these are "self cleaning" centrifuges,
            they can separate fluids with <strong>up to 5% (by volume) solids</strong>. Any ratio of the
            2 immiscible liquids can typically be handled by these types of centrifuges.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">Typical applications include:</p>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Separation of crude oil from salt-water and sediment</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Fuel oil separation from water and sediment</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>WVO (waste vegetable oil) separation from water and sediment</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span><a href="/waste-oil-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">Used motor oil separation</a> from water and fine metal particles</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Q5 -->
        <div id="q-decanter" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">
            What are the typical applications of a Decanter centrifuge?
          </h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            Decanter centrifuges are widely used for applications with <strong>more than 5% solids (up to 50%)</strong>
            by volume. They are designed for both 2-phase and 3-phase separation and handle continuous high-throughput
            solids discharge via an internal scroll conveyor.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">Typical decanter applications include:</p>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Crude oil tank bottom sludge</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Industrial and municipal wastewater</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Hemp biomass separation</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Chemical sludge thickening</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Oilfield drilling mud separation</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            See our full range of <a href="/alfa-laval-decanter-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:text-[#E8A317] transition-colors underline underline-offset-2">decanter centrifuge</a> options.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Q6 -->
        <div id="q-utilities" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
          <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">
            What are the utilities required for operation of industrial centrifuges? Do they consume a lot of power?
          </h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            Most industrial centrifuges operate on <strong>460 Volts AC power</strong>. Power requirements
            scale with capacity:
          </p>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span><strong>Small centrifuges (1–2 GPM):</strong> 1 HP motor</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span><strong>Large centrifuges (100+ GPM):</strong> 50 HP or larger motors</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
            <strong>Self-cleaning centrifuges</strong> additionally need:
          </p>
          <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>A clean, potable water supply for the sludge ejection mechanism — city water @ 50 psig is sufficient</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">›</span>
              <span>Some systems with integral sludge tanks and sludge pumps require compressed air, typically at 100 psig</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

